frequent_values: Project cataloging and analyzing material collected from a previous excavation in City Hall Park. Human and faunal remains, in addition to architecture, were analyzed.  In depth site history presented as well as extensive catalog of artifacts and that were found. Analysis focuses upon the burials and the massive and continual trash dumping that occurred throughout the site in the 18th century.

Project between Pearl, Pine, William and Wall Streets in the Financial District.  Report on the testing and mitigation of material from residential and commercial occupation.  Testing confirmed that no remnants of the late-17th century fortification wall, for which Wall Street is named, exist on the site.  19th- and 20th-century water system parts and construction elements were uncovered, as were 19th-century building foundations and a well.  The site's archaeological potential would have been better understood if the building records had been scrutinized to a closer degree before excavation.  All artifacts were catalogued and stored for further research.

Project in area bounded generally by East 13th Street, Avenue D/Pitt Street, 3rd Avenue/Bowery, and Delancey Street/Grand Street in the Lower East Side/East Village areas.  Though renovated, several 19th-century buildings exist on these lots and remains from the 19th to early-20th centuries such as privies, cisterns and Jewish ritual baths may exist underground.  In all, 262 sites in the project area are sensitive for archaeological remains.  Because this is a rezoning project on private property, no testing can be recommended despite the sensitivity of the area.  Many very detailed maps and photographs are included.

Project on Pearl and Whitehall Streets in the Financial District.  Five major time phases with corresponding archaeological material were uncovered, from a period spanning from 1640 through the mid-19th century.  Remains are mainly those of a mid-17th century warehouse.  The first of the four volumes of this report details the historical context, site reconstruction, and some artifact analysis; the second volume deals with artifact analysis, faunal analysis and conclusions; and the third and fourth contain data and notes.

Project in the Crotona Park East/West Farms neighborhoods in the Bronx. Potential for 19th century privies, cisterns, and wells, and in some cases burials from the Dutch Reformed Church and Hedger-Edwards cemeteries . Archaeological testing is recommended.

longest_values: Project area includes East 53rd Street between Second and Third Avenues, East 42nd Street between Second and Third Avenues, East 14th Street between Second and Third Avenues, Broome Street between Chrystie Street and the Bowery, and Grand Street between Chrystie Street and the Bowery. As there is a moderate chance of encountering findings of significance on East 53rd, 42nd, and Broome Streets, recommendations include that of new boring tests to evaluate the sensitivity of the site while particularly archaeologically rich areas would be further studied. The 14th Street site is considered unlikely to harbor archaeological remains though if boring tests were to indicate otherwise, this could refer to a rare Native American site that would be National Register eligible. Were a finding confirmed on this site, it is recommended that archaeological sites either be avoided in construction of the Second Avenue Subway or, if this were not possible, that proper recovery efforts be made to preserve findings. The Grand Street site is considered likely to hold remains from the Revolutionary War period. Additional soil boring tests are recommended.

Project on one of four sites: East 59th Street and 1st Avenue, 54th Street and 2nd Avenue, 61st Street between 1st and 2nd Avenues, and 59th Street and 2nd Avenue.  The 59th Street and 1st Avenue site, which is the preferred site for the project, is not sensitive for archaeological material; therefore no testing is needed.  Possible remnants of the 2nd Avenue subway and a tavern might exist at the 54th Street site; careful monitoring and archaeological consultation are recommended.  At 61st Street, the remains of an ink factory might exist; therefore archaeological testing is recommended.  The 59th Street and 2nd Avenue site does not warrant testing, because construction likely affected any present remains.  Maps and color photographs are included.  An addendum to the first report was made in order to include an additional site, between 55th and 56th Streets and from 1st to 3rd Avenues.  Mid-19th-century privies, wells and cisterns, as well as the remains of the 2nd Avenue subway, may exist on the site; as a result, potential construction at this site should be monitored.

Project roughly between Canal Street, Broadway, Park Place and St. James Place/Bowery in Manhattan.  Research and borings indicate that 19th- and 20th-century construction may have protected archaeological remains deeper below the surface.  On the "Courthouse Block" section of the project area, the remains of commercial development, tanyards, and residential development from the mid-18th to early-19th centuries may exist on the site, as well as those of a 19th-century slum and the East River outlet of the Collect Pond.  On the "Broadway Block" section, remains of an 18th-century African burial ground may exist.  18th- and 19th-century domestic and commercial remains, including backyard features, may also exist on the site.  This part of the site also has the potential to contain prehistoric remains, based on possible proximity to other deposits.  Testing is recommended, as is consideration of several existing structures for inclusion in the National Register of Historic Places.

Project by Goethals Bridge in Staten Island, New York.  Because of prehistoric and historic era materials found during earlier archaeological survey and testing  and this site’s proximity to Old Place Neck Site, a Woodland period Native American settlement, further testing and excavation was performed to see if this area was connected to the “Old Place” settlement and to better understand the context of the archaeological materials found. This testing found that prehistoric remains here were likely an extension of Old Place Neck site finds, and also indicated that the site was inhabited during other prehistoric and historic periods, including a wealth of remains from the mid-19th century.  While all useful information has likely been obtained from analysis of historic period use, further analysis and archaeological investigation of prehistoric use are recommended, and the site is recommended as eligible for listing in the National Register of Historic Places.

This report is the final volume in an assessment of the potential for preserved ancient landscape and submerged cultural remains within the New York and New Jersey Port District. This survey was undertaken as part of a proposal to deepen harbor waterways, including the Newark Bay, Claremont, Port Jersey, Anchorage, Stapleton, and Ambrose Channel. The survey implemented probing techniques to analyze site stratigraphy, date and examine sediment layers and to test for archaeological sensitivity in the region. This volume includes research on modern development within the harbor and documents the effects of recent improvements on the potential underwater sites. Furthermore, the report documents the integrity environmental and prehistoric remains within the region. 
This document contains two reports, one which listed above and Report no.108 detailing geomorphological and archaeological studies carried out at Governors Island as part of the same project.
